<div class="blog-faq">
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Is lip reduction surgery painful?</h3>
<p>The procedure is performed under local anesthesia, so you should not feel pain during the surgery. After the procedure, mild to moderate discomfort is normal and can be managed with prescribed pain medications. Most patients describe the discomfort as manageable and report that it subsides significantly within the first few days following surgery.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>How long do the results of lip reduction last?</h3>
<p>Lip reduction results are permanent. Once the excess tissue is removed and healing is complete, the new lip size and shape are maintained long-term. Unlike fillers, which require ongoing maintenance, lip reduction provides a lasting solution for patients who want smaller, more proportionate lips.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Will there be visible scars after lip reduction?</h3>
<p>The incisions for lip reduction are made inside the lip, along the wet-dry border, which means that resulting scars are typically hidden from view. Most patients find that scars are virtually invisible once fully healed. In rare cases where scarring is more noticeable, scar treatment options are available.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Can I combine lip reduction with other facial procedures?</h3>
<p>Yes, lip reduction can be combined with other facial cosmetic procedures such as rhinoplasty, chin augmentation, or facelift to achieve comprehensive facial rejuvenation. Combining procedures can reduce overall recovery time and produce more harmonious results. Dr. Johar will discuss the best approach for your goals during your consultation.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>How soon can I return to work after lip reduction surgery?</h3>
<p>Most patients can return to work and light activities within seven to ten days after surgery. Strenuous exercise and activities that risk impact to the face should be avoided for at least four to six weeks. Swelling may be present during the first week, so patients may prefer to take a few days off for privacy during the initial healing phase.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>What should I eat after lip reduction surgery?</h3>
<p>A soft diet is recommended for the first week to avoid irritating the incision sites and putting stress on the healing tissues. Foods like smoothies, yogurt, soup, mashed potatoes, and soft fruits are ideal. Avoid hot, spicy, and crunchy foods during the initial recovery period. Stay well-hydrated and follow all dietary guidelines provided by Dr. Johar.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Who is not a good candidate for lip reduction surgery?</h3>
<p>Active smokers, individuals with unrealistic expectations, patients with certain medical conditions that impair healing, and those who have not fully healed from recent lip procedures may not be ideal candidates. During your consultation, Dr. Johar will thoroughly evaluate your health and suitability for the procedure and discuss any concerns.</p>
</div>
</div>

